<HEADLINE>
<P>
METROPOLITAN DIGEST / LOS ANGELES COUNTY NEWS IN BRIEF: LOS ANGELES COUNTY; 
RETIRED CAPTAIN NAMED AS SHERIFF'S OMBUDSMAN 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 The Los Angeles County Board of Supervisors has selected a retired Los Angeles 
police captain, Rudy De Leon, 70, as the Sheriff Department's first ombudsman 
to hear citizen complaints lodged against the agency. 
</P>
<P>
 Establishment of an ombudsman was one of the recommendations of the 1992 
report prepared by special counsel James G. Kolts that called for reforms in 
the Sheriff's Department. 
</P>
<P>
 De Leon been special assistant to the state attorney general and deputy 
secretary of the state Youth and Adult Corrections agency. He will be paid 
$60,200 a year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
