<HEADLINE>
<P>
DIVISION II-A BOYS' BASKETBALL; TUSTIN'S DELAY CAN'T SLOW ROUT BY NO. 1 
DOMINGUEZ 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
By CHRIS FOSTER, TIMES STAFF WRITER 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Tustin High looked like the steppingstone it was meant to be Tuesday night. 
</P>
<P>
 Compton Dominguez, which came oh-so-close to a Southern Section title a year 
ago, stomped the Tillers, 70-35, in the Division II-A boys' semifinals at 
Compton College. Dominguez will play Bellflower St. John Bosco on Saturday. 
</P>
<P>
 It's a return engagement for the Dons (27-2), who lost to Riverside J.W. North 
by a point last season when Jamie Gillin missed a jumper at the buzzer. 
</P>
<P>
 "The way our kids looked at it, anything short of reaching the title game 
would have been an unsuccessful season," Dominguez Coach Russell Otis said. 
</P>
<P>
 Tustin (22-8) never had a chance. The Dons, the division's top-seeded team, 
were bigger, quicker and had more depth. 
</P>
<P>
 Oh, the Tillers took a stab at some strategy. They opened the game in a delay, 
trying to squeeze time off the clock. It didn't even delay the inevitable. 
</P>
<P>
 After nine possessions, Tustin was zero for six from the field and had four 
turnovers. The Tillers didn't even score until Doug Gottlieb made a layup with 
2 minutes 24 seconds left in the quarter. 
</P>
<P>
 The Dons, who have won 18 consecutive games, scored the first 11 points and 
were ahead, 19-2, at the end of the first quarter. 
</P>
<P>
 "They were overwhelming . . . just overwhelming," Tustin Coach Andy Ground 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 The Dons, who use five players 6 feet 4 or taller, outrebounded Tustin, 44-14. 
The Tillers have only one player taller than 6-3. 
</P>
<P>
 Tony Price scored 15 points and had 10 rebounds. Daryl Todd had 13 points and 
eight rebounds. Gillin had 11 and five. 
</P>
<P>
 "When a team pounds the glass like that against us, we have no chance," Ground 
said. 
</P>
<P>
 Dominguez got the Tillers down and made sure they stayed there with a stifling 
defense. The Dons led, 50-14, after three quarters. 
</P>
<P>
 Tustin made only 13 of 58 shots. So unnerved were the Tillers, that they threw 
up nine airballs. Gottlieb, the Tillers' leading scorer, had four. 
</P>
<P>
 Jeff Aguilar had made five three-pointers and scored 21 points in the 
quarterfinal victory over Pasadena Muir. He went scoreless, missing all seven 
of his shots. 
</P>
</TEXT>
