<HEADLINE>
<P>
EX-L.A. HOUSING DIRECTOR ENTERS CONTROLLER RACE 
</P>
</HEADLINE>
<BYLINE>
<P>
From a Times Staff Writer 
</P>
</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
 Kathleen Connell, a Westside financial consultant and former Los Angeles city 
housing director, declared her candidacy Tuesday for the Democratic nomination 
for state controller. 
</P>
<P>
 Connell, 47, portrayed herself in her announcement as an outsider who would 
challenge the spending of every state dollar to make sure nothing was wasted. 
</P>
<P>
 "I'm tired of reading about government officials abusing the system and 
wasting our money and of contractors cheating the system and collecting more 
than they're due," she said in a speech at Glendale Community College. 
</P>
<P>
 She chose for the announcement the college's computer training program that 
helps students prepare for jobs in high-technology industries. 
</P>
<P>
 "Our community college curriculum must be strengthened to reflect the needs of 
our industries who are, and will be, in a position to hire," she said. 
</P>
<P>
 Connell then went to Sacramento and San Francisco to repeat her announcement 
declaration. 
</P>
<P>
 Connell is the fourth Democrat to enter the race to succeed Democrat Gray 
Davis, who is running for lieutenant governor. Others are Assemblyman Rusty 
Arieas of San Jose, Alameda County Supervisor Don Peralta and Brad Sherman, 
chairman of the State Board of Equalization. 
</P>
<P>
 Republican candidates are former Assemblyman Tom McClintock and John Morris, 
heir to a department store fortune. 
</P>
<P>
 Connell holds a master's degree in urban planning and a Ph.D. in finance from 
UCLA. She is a former bank vice president and has taught at UCLA and UC 
Berkeley. She was Los Angeles city director of housing under Mayor Tom Bradley 
from 1977 to 1983. 
</P>
<P>
 After that, Connell founded her consulting company. Her firm provides 
financial and investment advice to local governments including the cities of 
Santa Monica, Los Angeles and San Diego, some California counties and special 
districts. 
</P>
<P>
 This is Connell's first campaign for elected office. By the end of last year, 
she had nearly $600,000 on hand to finance her campaign and raised more in a 
mid-February reception at the Century Plaza Hotel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
